
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `ctstat` baraye didan amalkarde container-ha (mesle Docker ya LXC) dar system shoma be kar mirevad. In dastoor be shoma etela'ati dar morede estefade az CPU, memory, va i/o disk container-ha midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `ctstat` --> 📊 Namayesh amalkarde hameye container-ha.
    🔹 `ctstat -n [tedad]` --> 🔢 Namayesh `tedad` az container-haie ke bishtarin resource ra estefade mikonand.
    🔹 `ctstat -i [interval]` --> ⏱ Update kardane etela'at har `interval` saniye.
    🔹 `ctstat -d` --> 💽 Namayesh etela'ate disk i/o.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ ctstat

    🔹 Namayesh amalkarde hameye container-ha.

    $ ctstat -n 5

    🔹 Namayesh 5 container-haie ke bishtarin CPU ra estefade mikonand.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ ctstat -i 2

    🔹 Har 2 saniye etela'ate amalkarde container-ha update mishavad. In be shoma komak mikonad ta be tore real-time estefade az resource-ha ra moshahede konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `ctstat` command is used to monitor the performance of containers (like Docker or LXC) on your system. It provides information about CPU usage, memory usage, and disk I/O of the containers.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `ctstat` --> 📊 Display the performance of all containers.
    🔹 `ctstat -n [number]` --> 🔢 Display the top `number` of containers using the most resources.
    🔹 `ctstat -i [interval]` --> ⏱ Update the information every `interval` seconds.
    🔹 `ctstat -d` --> 💽 Display disk I/O information.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ ctstat

    🔹 Display the performance of all containers.

    $ ctstat -n 5

    🔹 Display the top 5 containers using the most CPU.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ ctstat -i 2

    🔹 Update the container performance information every 2 seconds. This helps you to monitor resource usage in real-time.
